Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Note: I began by creating code and debuigging train_model.py, as this is a prerequisite to running hpo.py. There was a lot of Google-searching and external resource-gathering involved, as many of the concepts required were not covered during the lecture material - for example, defining a dataset based on an ImageFolder. This, plus extensive wait times while waiting for estimator.fit() and tuner.fit() to run, only to find some simple syntax error, caused a lot of grief. Therefore, it is paramount to ensure the remote train_model.py script runs correctly first.

from sagemaker.debugger import Rule, DebuggerHookConfig, ProfilerRule, rule_configs

rules = [
    Rule.sagemaker(rule_configs.vanishing_gradient()),
    Rule.sagemaker(rule_configs.overfit()),
    Rule.sagemaker(rule_configs.overtraining()),
    Rule.sagemaker(rule_configs.poor_weight_initialization()),
    Rule.sagemaker(rule_configs.loss_not_decreasing()),
    ProfilerRule.sagemaker(rule_configs.LowGPUUtilization()),
    ProfilerRule.sagemaker(rule_configs.ProfilerReport()),
]

from sagemaker.debugger import ProfilerConfig, FrameworkProfile

debugger_config = DebuggerHookConfig(
    hook_parameters={"train.save_interval": "100", "eval.save_interval": "10"}
)

profiler_config = ProfilerConfig(
    system_monitor_interval_millis=500, framework_profile_params=FrameworkProfile(num_steps=10)
)

HPO Tuning¶

Now, we define and run the actual tuning job. Initially I had defined learning rate as a continuous parameter, but this lead to sub-optimal optimization; how could an optimzation algorithm choose from a continuous distribution with only 4 evaluations? I had intended to run 8 total (4 in parallel), but AWS did not allow more than 2 instances in parallel, so I left it with the initial 4 jobs total (2 in parallel).

My choices for hyper parameters are basic, but defining the learning rate as a categorical parameter, using the rule of 3 - increasing the LR by a factor of 3 - provides 3 choices total.

Additionally, too many choices for batch size could lead to suboptimal results from the total optimization space. So here similarly I limited to only 2 possibilities, which should allow the optimizer to better find the best options.

In this example, only 6 total combinations of hyperparameters are possible, and I evaluate 4 total. If this were a real case, I would run many more total cases (at least 8-16), using more levels of each parameter (higher learning rate spread, higher batch-size spread) to get a better assessment of the response.

Initially I set this up with epochs as a further hyperparameter, but given the limited design space, it seemed that with varying epochs would simply improve loss as epochs went up. So I removed epochs and kept it as "5" in the hpo.py file, with the intent to double epochs for finetuning later.

from sagemaker.tuner import (
    IntegerParameter,
    CategoricalParameter,
    ContinuousParameter,
    HyperparameterTuner,
)

hyperparameter_ranges={
    "lr": CategoricalParameter([0.001,0.003,0.01]),
    "batch-size": CategoricalParameter([8,32])
}

objective_metric_name="average test loss"
objective_type="Minimize"
metric_definitions=[{"Name":"average test loss","Regex":"Test set: Average loss: ([0-9\\.]+)"}]

estimator = PyTorch(
    entry_point="hpo.py",
    role=role,
    py_version='py36',
    framework_version="1.8",
    instance_count=1,
    instance_type="ml.g4dn.xlarge",
    profiler_config=profiler_config,
    debugger_hook_config=debugger_config,
    rules=rules,
)

tuner = HyperparameterTuner(
    estimator,
    objective_metric_name,
    hyperparameter_ranges,
    metric_definitions,
    max_jobs=4,
    max_parallel_jobs=2,
    objective_type=objective_type,
)

Model Deployment Woes¶

There were many challenges to getting a model to deploy, and little debugging information given by AWS.

First, I was using the same ml.g4dn instance to provide GPU inference. However, there was an issue loading smdebug (from my train_models.py script, which worked fine while traininG). But, AWS CloudWatch did not give any information on this error; I sat there, burning g4dn inference hours, trying to debug my model, setup, learn the whole method for deploying models via a .py script (as it was not taught in class).

Eventually, after trying the model on a ml.m5.xlarge endpoint, I finally got the error about smdebug; I removed those lines and re-trained the model, re-deployed the endpoint, to get another error about hooks not being defined.

At this point, my AWS session burned through $25 of costs, so I had to go back to the session from a previous course. However, there while training, the model was not deploying correctly still.

Finally, I manually created my own model.tar.gz using the model.pth and a custom endpoint.py file; I manually created a model within Sagemaker (external to this notebook), and deployed an endpoint. Therefore, "deployment" is covered externally and here I simply refer to the deployed endpoint.

def predict_image_from_path(imagepath2):
    pilimage2=Image.open(imagepath2)
    image2=testing_transform(pilimage2)
    nparray2=asarray(image2)

    pred2=np.argmax(response2)+1
    print("Predicted class is: "+str(pred2))
    print("File path, including image class is: "+imagepath2)
    return response2
